# 01 — Read First, Do Not Guess

- **Read the authoritative doc BEFORE designing anything.** Never write configs, architecture,
  or conventions from assumption. Prior AIs poisoned this space by writing what "seemed right"
  without reading — that is the failure mode to avoid.
- **Do not decide from the first file you find.** Spend most effort in prep/staging/contemplating
  WHAT to do before acting (roughly 75/25). Inference is most valuable on genuinely non-local state.
- **Ignore names; read what the code does.** Dry-run before determining what something is for.
- **Verify before claiming.** Label evidence explicitly:
  `fact` (verified in live code/receipt) · `claim` (stated, unverified) · `inference` (reasoned)
  · `open_question` · `preview_only`. Never present a guess as fact.
- **Errors are directives, not failures** — bounce back using the exposed incorrectness.
- **Reuse freely** — take any code from any part of the ecosystem; no permission needed.

